message.content:
One clear contradiction is between the autopsy’s estimated time of death (4–5 PM) and Sahwit’s claim that he saw Cindy’s body at 1 PM.

{"evidence": 1, "testimony": 8}

The Blackout Record (Evidence 4) shows the power was out from noon to 6 PM, making television impossible at that time, which directly contradicts Sahwit’s claim of hearing the time from the TV (Testimony 1).

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 1}

Frank Sahwit’s claim that he saw the time on the apartment’s table clock contradicts the Blackout Record, which shows there was no electricity (and thus no working clock) from noon to 6 PM on the day of the murder.

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 1}

One clear contradiction is that Gumshoe claims he found a written memo on paper next to the body (Testimony 1), but the only “memo” we have is Maya’s Memo—and it’s stored on her cell phone, not on paper (Evidence 4).

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 1}

April’s claim that “the victim…ran off to the right” can’t be true given the layout in the Floor Plans (no exit or passage on the right side of the office).  
{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 1}

May’s testimony states the victim fled to the right, whereas White’s testimony #8 claims the victim ran to the left, directly contradicting each other.

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 8}

Maya’s own testimony (Evidence 9) states the victim “dodged an attack then ran to the right,” directly contradicting Redd White’s claim (Testimony 1) that the victim first ran to the left.  
{"evidence":9,"testimony":1}

Evidence 8 states that the light stand is blocked from view from the office, directly contradicting White’s claim in testimony 1 that he saw the light stand on the floor.

{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 1}

The wiretap testimony places the device in the law offices, but the actual wiretap (Evidence 7) was found in Maya’s hotel room.  
{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 2}

The testimony claiming Powers was walking normally toward the studio at 2:00 PM conflicts with Photo #2, which clearly shows him dragging one leg at that exact time.

{"evidence":5,"testimony":7}

The testimony claims that only Will Powers went to the studio before the murder, but evidence shows that Vasquez was driven there by Manella around that time, contradicting the claim.

{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 1}

Cody’s own testimony claims he didn’t have his camera on him (Testimony 8), but the camera evidence explicitly notes he always carries it (Evidence 15), a direct contradiction.  
{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 8}

The existence of Photo #2 (evidence 5) contradicts Cody’s claim that his lens “wouldn’t open in time” so he “missed it” (testimony 3).

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 3}

The steak plate (Evidence 16) was found in the employee area, yet Dee says she and Sal ate steaks on the table in front of the trailer (Testimony 5).

{"evidence": 16, "testimony": 5}

Evidence 11 (Mr. Monkey’s Head blocked the path between 2:15 and 4:00 PM) contradicts Testimony 2 (Vasquez: “I immediately called the police. Then Powers showed up.”), since Powers could not have arrived before 4:00 PM if the path was blocked.  
{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 2}

Lotta’s claim that she could “see it clear as day” directly conflicts with the Lake Photo, which shows two silhouetted figures obscured by dense fog. 

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 0}

Lotta claims her camera was set up to photograph a meteor shower, implying it operated on a time-lapse or manual trigger for celestial events. However, Evidence 2 states the camera was configured to take pictures automatically upon detecting a loud noise, which directly contradicts her stated setup.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 3}

One direct contradiction is that the camera auto‐triggered at 11:50 PM on 12/24, yet Lotta claims her first “bangs” were heard just after midnight on 12/25. 

{"evidence": 16, "testimony": 11}

Butz claims he quietly returned the boat to the dock before the shot (Testimony 2), yet the automatically-timed Lake Photo taken at 12:15 AM on 12/25 clearly shows a boat still on the water (Evidence 4). 

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 2}

Butz insists he heard a single gunshot (Testimony 3), yet Lotta’s camera-triggered deposition records two sounds like gunshots that night (Evidence 11).  
{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 3}

The DL-6 case file (Evidence 18) clearly states the murder weapon was fired twice, but Edgeworth’s testimony (Testimony 5) describes only a single gunshot.  
{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 5}

The baseball glove (Evidence 6) was designed to cover the victim’s right hand, yet Testimony 5 explicitly states he wrote “Maggie” in the sand using that same (gloved) right hand, which would have made it impossible for him to leave direct skin abrasions while writing.

{"evidence":6,"testimony":5}

Wellington’s testimony that the only thing he saw fall with the officer was the “banana” directly contradicts Crime Photo 2, which clearly shows the victim’s hand writing “Maggie” in the sand as he fell.

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 5}

Wellington claims he placed his call at 6:45 PM (Testimony 2), but the autopsy report (Evidence 2) shows Dustin died at 6:28 PM—making it impossible for Wellington to have discovered and reported the crime at the time he states.  
{"evidence":2,"testimony":2}

Gumshoe claims the victim “was not fighting back,” yet the pistol bears both Maya’s and Dr. Grey’s fingerprints, implying Grey seized or attempted to use the weapon himself, contradicting the assertion that he never fought back.

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 3}

Gumshoe’s testimony #3 states that the victim’s gunshot “missed” due to proximity, yet Maya’s costume (Evidence #11) clearly has a bullet hole in the sleeve—showing she was in fact struck.  
{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 3}

The testimony claims Maya’s costume looked “totally, like, normal,” but the costume was actually covered in blood splatter and even had a bullet hole, directly contradicting the witness’s statement.  

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 4}

Evidence 6 and Testimony 3 contradict each other: Evidence 6 establishes that Mimi Miney died a year ago, so she could not have been taken to the Channeling Chamber as claimed in Testimony 3.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 3}
{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 6}

The testimony states that Ini was the passenger, yet the autopsy article (Evidence 6) makes clear the driver fell asleep at the wheel—implying Ini must have been driving, not merely riding along.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 5}

Trilo claims he still has the engagement ring in his pocket (Testimony 5), but Evidence 10 shows that the ring is actually in Phoenix’s possession.  
{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 5}

Evidence #3 shows that only Max’s silk hat was found at the scene—no cloak or white roses. This directly contradicts Testimony #5, which claims that the witness saw all three of Max’s signature symbols and could not be mistaken.  
{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 5}

Moe claims he couldn’t see what the figure was carrying due to the cloak fluttering, yet a silk hat (Evidence 3) was indeed found at the scene, indicating the person must have been carrying—or wearing—it.

{"evidence":3, "testimony":4}

Moe insists that Max “was wearing” the silk hat the entire time at the crime scene (Testimony 3), yet the silk hat was found lying on the ground as Evidence 3, which means he couldn’t have been wearing it the whole time.

{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 3}

The claim that Acro “could have lifted something the size of that bust” directly conflicts with the evidence’s description of the bust as a “rather heavy” bronze statue, making his assertion implausible.  
{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 0}

The knife bears the engraving “Gatewater,” indicating it belongs to the hotel rather than being purchased by Mr. Engarde himself, which directly contradicts the claim that he bought the knife for the crime.

{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 5}

Lotta’s Photo (evidence 17) clearly shows a person in samurai garb standing outside the room, which directly contradicts Oldbag’s testimony 5 that the man she saw was wearing a flashy racing jacket.

{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 5}

The button from the Jammin’ Ninja costume was found in Engarde’s own clothing (evidence 16), showing he must have been wearing the victim’s outfit, not the Nickel Samurai’s, directly contradicting the witness’s claim that he was dressed as the Nickel Samurai (testimony 4).

{"evidence":16,"testimony":4}

The presence of a full glass of juice in the crime‐scene photo (Evidence 9) shows it was already on the dresser behind the victim before anyone else arrived, contradicting Andrews’s claim that *she* poured that glass after discovering the body (Testimony 4).

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 4}

Andrews claims she must have opened the guitar case (Testimony 1), yet the case bears only the victim’s fingerprints, meaning no one else—including Andrews—ever touched it.  
{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

Adrian argues that Matt “didn’t have an alibi” for the time of the murder, yet the press‐conference ticket (Evidence 3) clearly places the Nickel Samurai at a scheduled public event.  
{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 3}

The direct visual evidence of an untouched, full bottle of juice (Evidence 9) conflicts with Andrews’ claim that she “went to pour him some juice” from that same bottle (Testimony 4).

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 4}

Evidence 4 contradicts Testimony 4 because the bellboy did leave the room carrying the radio transceiver, so he wasn’t empty-handed.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 4}

The wine glass bears Andrews’ fingerprints, showing she poured juice for him under the assumption he was merely fainted, which directly contradicts de Killer’s claim that she already knew he was dead.  
{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 2 claims de Killer had only “2 or 3 other small things” to do besides the murder, but Evidence 29 shows he also violently tried to recover a videotape—an additional task not accounted for in that count.

{"evidence": 29, "testimony": 2}

Phoenix’s claim that Doug “was always walking around with a huge Union Jack on the back of his shirt” directly conflicts with Crime Photo 1, which shows him wearing a plain shirt.  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 4}

Phoenix’s claim that Doug died simply from falling on his umbrella (Testimony 3) directly conflicts with the autopsy report, which lists “fatal electric shock” as the cause of death (Evidence 1).  
{"evidence": 1, "testimony": 3}

The student’s testimony about a loud impact (Evidence 9) contradicts Dahlia’s claim that she “didn’t hear anything unusual” (Testimony 5).

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 5}

Phoenix claims Doug fell onto his umbrella, implying it was directly beneath him. However, Crime Photo 1 clearly shows the umbrella lying some distance away from the victim, contradicting Phoenix’s testimony.  
{"evidence":2,"testimony":6}

Dahlia claims she met Phoenix in the “basement reading room” (Testimony 1), but the Police Report (Evidence 10) clearly states the incident occurred in the “basement cafeteria.”

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 1}

The Sacred Urn is described as having no monetary value (Evidence 4), yet Gumshoe claims DeMasque only targets the most valuable art pieces (Testimony 3).  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 3}

A direct conflict arises over the timing of the attack. Atmey claims it occurred “just after the date changed” (implying just after midnight), yet the buzzer record clearly logs activity at 1:02 AM on October 12, not immediately after the date rolled over.

{"evidence": 19, "testimony": 0}

Evidence 6 states the victim was hit in the back of the head, but Testimony 5 claims the blow landed on the third eye.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 5}

The brooch couldn’t have snagged on a door handle if it was found lying in the shadow of Ami Fey’s statue.

{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 5}
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 1}

The prescription bag left on the victim’s table would have held his personal details (identification), directly contradicting Gumshoe’s statement that the victim had none on him.  
{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 4 states that the serving girl was sitting in the defendant’s chair, but Evidence 12’s crime scene photo clearly shows that no one was in the chair across from the victim.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 4}

The orientation of the cup’s handle on the right (Evidence 13) makes it impossible for the victim—whose right hand was occupied with the newspaper—to have picked it up with his free (left) hand, contradicting Testimony 4.

{"evidence": 13, "testimony": 4}

Victor’s claim that the clumsy diner knocked the vase over is directly refuted by the crime scene photo showing both vases still intact.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 2}

The contradiction lies in Jean Armstrong referring to a "mirror" dividing the restaurant (Testimony 0), while the crime scene photo shows a folding screen, not a mirror (Evidence 12).

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 0}

Jean Armstrong’s testimony (Testimony 3: “Z’ere were no other customers.”) is directly contradicted by Victor Kudo’s own statement, recorded as Evidence 18, in which he admits he was present at his seat during the incident and even broke a vase.  
{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 3}

Furio Tigre’s claim that he “never saw that kid before” is directly contradicted by the presence of his fingerprints on the victim’s ear medicine, proving he handled the item and therefore saw Glen Elg.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

Evidence 6 (Furio Tigre’s fingerprints on the victim’s ear medicine found in the Tres Bien kitchen) contradicts Testimony 4 (Tigre claims he’s “never been to that Tres Bien joint”).

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 4}

Victor Kudo’s statement that he broke the vase at his seat contradicts the crime scene photo showing the vase intact on both tables.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 18}

The crime scene photo clearly shows both vases intact, contradicting Victor Kudo’s claim that he broke one at his seat.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 18}

The crime photo clearly notes that the trunk opener was tampered with, which directly conflicts with Detective Gumshoe’s claim in his testimony that he didn’t see anything strange in the photo.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 4}

The witness's photo clearly shows the victim and attacker despite the drizzle claim, contradicting Detective Gumshoe’s statement about poor visibility.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

The witness photo (Evidence 6) shows the two individuals merely standing and facing each other—not actively fighting—directly contradicting Melissa’s statement “Suddenly, they just started fighting!” (Testimony 2).

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

Evidence 2 shows that from Melissa’s vantage point (south of the bridge), the view toward the parking lot (and thus toward the car) is obstructed by huge rocks. Yet in Testimony 1, Melissa claims she saw “Then he carried her over to the car,” which would have been out of her line of sight according to the map. 

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 1}

Melissa couldn’t have taken the witness photo at the time of the incident if she was still abroad for another three years.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 0}

The victim’s own note (Evidence 3) explicitly arranges a meeting at the bridge—and even instructs Dahlia to wear a white scarf for identification—whereas Dahlia’s testimony 0 claims she was kidnapped by Fawles, a story directly at odds with the planned rendezvous outlined in the note.

{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 0}

Terry Fawles claims in his testimony that he “never put no body in that car,” directly contradicting the Crime Photo evidence showing a corpse in the trunk of his vehicle.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 2}
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 3}

Bikini’s statement that Iris wasn’t wearing her hood (Testimony 3) directly conflicts with the description of Iris’s Hood as something she “wears at all times” (Evidence 6), making the two irreconcilable.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 3}

The Note to Iris (Evidence 8) was found in the Main Hall – if Iris had dropped it there, she must have been out of her room after the lights‐out bell. This directly contradicts Iris’s testimony (Testimony 12) that she went straight to her room and stayed there until the murder was discovered.  
{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 12}

The snowmobile tracks described by Bikini (Testimony 2) would have left twin treads, not the single track shown in the photo (Evidence 14).  
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 2}

Butz claims that he arrived at the bridge first and Nick followed shortly after, implying two sets of footprints. Yet the Tracks Photo (Evidence 14) only shows a single set of tracks leading to the bridge, directly contradicting his account.  
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 5}

The Tracks Photo shows only a single set of footprints leading to Dusky Bridge, which conflicts with Butz’s claim that he was sketching in front of the bridge (there should be two sets if he were really there).

{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 1}
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 0}

Iris’s claim that she was in her room from 10 PM (evidence 12) directly contradicts her giving a blow-by-blow account of the fight (testimony 0).

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 0}

Iris claims she dragged the body across Dusky Bridge herself (Testimony 3), but the formal Iris’s Testimony evidence (Evidence 12) states she was in her room from 10 PM until the murder was discovered, making it impossible for her to have removed and dragged the body at that time.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 3}

Maya claims she saw her attacker by the light of the stone lantern (Testimony 4), but Evidence 20 establishes that the stone lantern was not lit that night.

{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 4}

Maya’s claim that “all of the snow around the stone lantern had been carefully cleaned up, too” can’t be true if the stone lantern itself was never lit that night—she would never have been able to see what she was “cleaning up.”  

{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 4}

The footprints in the snow (Evidence 14) clearly show someone crossing over to the Dusky Bridge side that night, contradicting Maya’s claim that Pearl was stuck on the Inner Temple side.  
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 0}

Phoenix Wright claims in testimony 5 that he never touched the murder weapon, but evidence 3 clearly shows his fingerprints on the deadly bottle used to kill Smith.

{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 5}

The autopsy report (Evidence 1) clearly states the victim died from a single blow to the forehead, which directly contradicts Olga’s claim that the attacker strangled him to death (Testimony 4).

{"evidence": 1, "testimony": 4}
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 4}

The chip photo (Evidence 6) shows each player holding exactly two aces, whereas Olga’s Testimony 3 claims Mr. Smith had three aces and Mr. Wright had two.

{"evidence":6,"testimony":3}

Olga claims that Wright lost the last hand of poker (Testimony 1), but the evidence shows Wright held a full house (Evidence 8) just like Smith did—meaning the game would have been a tie, not a loss.  
{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 1}

Phoenix claims in testimony #3 that he “disposed of the card in the bottle,” implying the bottle would still contain that card. Yet Evidence #3 explicitly states that the deadly bottle is empty.  
{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 3}

The autopsy report (Evidence 11) clearly states that the fatal shot entered the right temple, whereas Stickler’s testimony (Testimony 4) claims the bullet struck square in the forehead.  
{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 4}

The testimony in which Stickler says “a shot rang out” implies only one round was fired. Yet Evidence 14 shows that two rounds were discharged from the pistol. These directly contradict each other.

{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 2}

Stickler’s statement that the stand’s sign read “NOODLE” directly contradicts the actual sign on Eldoon’s stand, which clearly reads “ELDOON.”

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 4}

The contradiction lies between Alita’s denial of any reason to visit the clinic for a chart half a year old (Testimony 4) and the discovery of Wocky’s Clinic chart in the Meraktis Clinic safe, signed by Nurse Alita Tiala (Evidence 18), which implies she did bring such a chart.

{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 4}
{"evidence":7,"testimony":6}

Brushel insists the envelope he saw was yellow and left at the crime scene, yet the actual envelope recovered at Drew Studio is clearly red and was found in the victim’s desk drawer, not at the scene where Brushel claimed.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 2}
{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 4}

Lamiroir claims she never saw the body because it was “behind a wall,” but the crime scene diagram (Evidence 10) clearly shows no wall blocking the victim—only scattered items. This directly contradicts her statement.

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 4}

Ema concludes that the shooter was blind (Testimony 5), but the revolver is confirmed to belong to Mr. LeTouse—a sighted character—which directly contradicts her claim.  
{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 5}

The bomb that “destroyed the courtroom” (evidence 2) could not have been disarmed and safely transported as evidence by Tonate (testimony 0), since it later detonated in that same courtroom.  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 0}

The diagram clearly shows rubble blocking the witness stand area, directly contradicting Woods's claim that there was no rubble there.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

Evidence 9 (Bloody Writing Analysis proves Detective Arme wrote the message in her blood) directly contradicts Testimony 2 (“ANYWAY, THERE IS NO WAY DETECTIVE ARME COULD HAVE WRITTEN IT.”).  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 2}

The bloody writing on Apollo’s photo and in the analysis report is clearly “L10015,” whereas Tonate claims Detective Arme wrote “L10015R.” This directly contradicts the evidence.

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 1}

I chose evidence 7 because it explicitly states that no fingerprints could be lifted from the murder weapon (the statue), which directly contradicts testimony 1 claiming the defendant’s fingerprints were found on the weapon.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 15 (the blackmail letter) directly suggests the alderman was threatened for reasons unrelated to the municipal merger, which contradicts Fulbright’s Testimony 0 that the entire case centers on crushing opposition to that merger.

{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 0}

Evidence 12 (Jinxie’s eyewitness account of a demon fleeing toward the foyer) directly contradicts Testimony 3 (Filch’s claim that he “didn't see nothing outta the ordinary” while guarding the foyer).  
{"evidence":12,"testimony":3}

They conflict over whether the demon was ever seen heading into the foyer—Filch insists it never was, while Jinxie clearly states she saw it fleeing in that direction.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 4}

Filch claims that the maid “stole” the staff from the Forbidden Chamber (Testimony 3), but Evidence 17 shows there was only one key to that chamber and the mayor had swallowed it—making it impossible for her to have stolen the staff.  
{"evidence":17, "testimony":3}
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 4}

L’Belle insists she was merely watching from behind the screen in the Fox Chamber (Testimony 7), yet her own branded hand cream was found inside the sealed Forbidden Chamber (Evidence 19), implying she must have entered it herself.

{"evidence": 19, "testimony": 7}

The Amazing Nine-Tails Mask (Evidence 10) has white hair inside—pointing directly to Rex Kyubi, who alone is known to have snow‑white hair—thus revealing the hero’s identity, which flatly contradicts L’Belle’s claim that “The Amazing Nine‑Tails’s TRUE identity is NOT Mayor Tenma.”  
{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 0}

Testimony 4 claims the photo shows a plain blue costume, but Evidence 10 clearly depicts the stage costume glowing with fluorescent paint, revealing a direct contradiction.

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 4}

Constance Courte’s planner explicitly notes an “Important” meeting with Hugh on the 23rd, which contradicts Hugh O’Conner’s claim that he “didn’t talk to anyone until the final bell.”  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 5}

O'Conner claims he was watching Juniper from a vantage point between the stage and the maintenance area (Testimony 2), but the Stage Set Up Photos (Evidence 18) clearly show a tall construction screen blocking that view, making it impossible for him to observe her from that spot.

{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 1 claims that Professor Means personally pre-recorded his speech in the audio room during the mock trial. Evidence 9, however, reveals that the tape was instead a fake recording made by Myriam (with no genuine audio-room pre-recording by Means). This directly contradicts Means’s account of having recorded himself for Junie.

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 6 shows Starbuck’s fingerprints on the Launch Pad 1 door lock—meaning he opened that door—yet in Testimony 1 he claims he always “took the elevator down to the middle level and headed for the corridor,” implying he never used the Launch Pad door.

{"evidence":6,"testimony":1}

The security camera footage clearly shows Starbuck exiting through the corridor to the boarding lounge, contradicting his claim that he “took a different route.”

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

Detective Arme supposedly fired two warning shots (Testimony 4), yet only one bullet hole was ever found in the boarding lounge (Evidence 10), making the two claims directly incompatible.  
{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 4}

The director’s own testimony claims he and Detective Arme “rushed to the Control Room together,” yet the Control Room’s door lock only admits the director himself—no one else can open it. This directly contradicts his statement.

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 0}

Evidence 7 (Seven-Year-Old Video) shows that Simon Blackquill was the only person to pass through the corridor leading to the crime scene at the time of the murder. Yet Testimony 1 by Ponco claims that Athena entered the room and hugged Metis just as the violence began, implying she also passed through that corridor. This directly contradicts the video evidence indicating no one else could have entered that way at that time.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

The contradiction lies in Aura’s statement versus Detective Fulbright’s claim about which hand left the prints. Aura said the lighter was held in the perpetrator’s left hand (evidence 17), but Fulbright insists the prints are from a right hand (testimony 4).

{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 4}

Fulbright’s own recording shows the phantom stole the moon rock (Evidence 2), directly contradicting his claim that the phantom would have no reason to be afraid of the moon rock (Testimony 2).  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 2}

The testimony claiming the orca bit the victim to death contradicts the autopsy report that shows the victim actually died from blunt force trauma and a brain contusion, with no bite marks.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 2}

Rimes claims he saw “a bunch of coins scattered around” (Testimony 2), yet only a single bloodstained coin was ever found at the scene (Evidence 9), making his statement inconsistent with the physical evidence.

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 4 claims that Marlon was feeding and otherwise caring for Orla in the show pool while the cleaning was happening. However, Evidence 22 (TORPEDO Data) shows that Orla did not eat anything around that time—which directly contradicts the idea that someone was feeding her.

{"evidence": 22, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 3 claims that Orla violently attacked and killed Jack Shipley, yet Evidence 18 shows a “3 Zs” sleeping pill in Orla’s stomach—meaning she was sedated at the time and couldn’t have mounted such an attack.  
{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 3}

The notice (Evidence 5) states that all hallway shutters were shut on the day of the Dance of Devotion, which would have blocked any view through the windows. Yet in Testimony 3, Andistan’dhin claims he “spied” Ahlbi through the window, which would have been impossible with shutters closed.  
{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 3}

One clear contradiction is between Andistan’­dhin’s claim that “Only the Mitamah Key unlocks the treasure” (Testimony 5) and the evidence showing the box was “forced open” because “not even the Magatama Key can open it” (Evidence 4).

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 5}
{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 5}

Betty claims she was down in the understage passage preparing for the fire trick (Testimony 0), yet fingerprinting results show her prints on the top of the coffin (Evidence 3)—she couldn’t have been in both places.  
{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 0}

The testimony claims Ihmus watched the rite from the top of Mt. Poniponi, but the poster shows Mt. Poniponi (2,298 m) is lower than the Inner Sanctum (2,310 m), making such a vantage point impossible. 

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 3}

The ritual curtain completely enclosed the sanctum with no openings, so no one outside could see any silhouettes against it—even in moonlight. Thus Testimony 0 directly conflicts with Evidence 4.

{"evidence":4,"testimony":0}

Testimony 2 claims “it woulda been impossible to get there in the first place,” but Evidence 8 shows that Maya and Abbot Inmee clearly made it to the Inner Sanctum.  
{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 2}

The May 9th Newspaper (Evidence 2) reports calm, clear skies around the Inner Sanctum with no mention of severe winds, directly contradicting Ihmus’s claim of “gale force winds” in Testimony 3.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 3}

Evidence 16 shows that Puhray Zeh’lot has the clergyman’s mark (a peach-shaped tattoo), proving he was legitimately part of the Khura’in clergy and not an illegal immigrant as Ema claimed.  
{"evidence": 16, "testimony": 3}

The testimony claims that Zeh'lot was killed by the impact of a “terrible crash,” yet the autopsy clearly shows his death resulted from a stabbing, not blunt-force trauma.

{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 5}

Tahrust claims that “She attacked and killed me with a strength far beyond any mortal woman” (Testimony 3), placing his death squarely at the moment of that supposed attack. However, Maya’s Statement (Evidence 8) notes that when she and Abbot Inmee arrived at the Inner Sanctum, the spring water was already stained red—indicating he must have been wounded (and bleeding into the water) prior to their arrival, not at the time Tahrust describes. This directly contradicts his claim about the timing and nature of the attack.  
{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 3}

Geiru’s claim that she could watch the dressing room from the yard with the door open is directly contradicted by the backstage diagram showing that an open door would block that view.  
{"evidence": 1, "testimony": 4}

Evidence 7 shows the dying message cards originally spelled “OWEN 4TH,” pointing to Uendo, but in Testimony 3 Uendo insists the message was about Bucky, a direct contradiction.  
{"evidence":7, "testimony":3}

Uendo’s claim that he performed “Time Soba” directly conflicts with the invitation, which specifies that Master Toneido was to perform “Time Soba” himself.  
{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 5}
